&lt;/div>&lt;p>In TAC, we now have a new option called &lt;strong>Resource Account&lt;/strong> next to the existing &lt;strong>Voice App&lt;/strong> option. This way, we can choose if we want to forward calls to a resource account associated with a voice app or to a voice app directly.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-1.png"
width="1501"
height="902"
srcset="https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-1_hu_2e793513d52c7d71.png 480w, https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-1_hu_fc5113ba50aa2f4d.png 1024w"
loading="lazy"
decoding="async"
alt="New Options in TAC"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="166"
data-flex-basis="399px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This is actually a bit confusing to me. As I recall, the option to transfer to another attendant or queue was always called &lt;strong>Voice app&lt;/strong> before but it was actually referencing resource accounts. I checked one of my previous blog &lt;a class="link" href="https://heusser.pro/p/microsoft-teams-auto-attendants-what-you-didnt-know-part-2-iz5ftexar5sq" >posts&lt;/a> and found this screenshot where it&amp;rsquo;s clearly visible that the &lt;strong>Voice app&lt;/strong> is in fact referencing a the UPN of a resource account.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-3.png"
width="1024"
height="634"
srcset="https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-3_hu_9f6782efd3bc99f6.png 480w, https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-3_hu_4d758a3f9ac98340.png 1024w"
loading="lazy"
decoding="async"
alt="Old screenshot"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="161"
data-flex-basis="387px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>When we look at the voice menu in TAC again after the change, we can see that the existing options which previously said &lt;strong>Voice app&lt;/strong> are now called &lt;strong>Resource account&lt;/strong>. I&amp;rsquo;ve replaced the third menu option with a &lt;strong>Voice App&lt;/strong> now.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>&lt;img src="https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-4.png"
width="1482"
height="500"
srcset="https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-4_hu_a0d5bb30b1b51d44.png 480w, https://heusser.pro/p/m365-call-flow-visualizer-update-support-nested-voice-apps-without-resource-accounts-hjm1e1w9m0h8/image-4_hu_782b1148aab2835c.png 1024w"
loading="lazy"
decoding="async"
alt="New labels"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="296"
data-flex-basis="711px"
>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>So, existing configs referencing resource accounts that were previously labeled &lt;strong>Voice app&lt;/strong> are now called &lt;strong>Resource accounts&lt;/strong> and if you want to reference a voice app, you&amp;rsquo;ll need to select &lt;strong>Voice app&lt;/strong>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Let&amp;rsquo;s look at the PowerShell output again. Notice how the third option now says &lt;strong>ConfigurationEndpoint&lt;/strong> and not &lt;strong>ApplicationEndpoint&lt;/strong> anymore. Both options are valid configurations and can be mixed and matched as you need but it&amp;rsquo;s important to understand the difference.&lt;/p>
